abstract.textEnglish: This article reports measurements of the angle between differently defined jet axes in pp collisions at <inline-formula id="IEq2"> <mml:math display="inline"> <mml:msqrt> <mml:mi>s</mml:mi> </mml:msqrt> </mml:math> <tex-math id="IEq2_TeX">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$$ \sqrt{s} $$\end{document}</tex-math> </inline-formula> = 5 .02 TeV carried out by the ALICE Collaboration. Charged particles at midrapidity are clustered into jets with resolution parameters R = 0 .2 and 0.4. The jet axis, before and after Soft Drop grooming, is compared to the jet axis from the Winner-Takes-All (WTA) recombination scheme. The angle between these axes, ∆ R <sub>axis</sub>, probes a wide phase space of the jet formation and evolution, ranging from the initial high-momentum-transfer scattering to the hadronization process. The ∆ R <sub>axis</sub> observable is presented for 20 < <inline-formula id="IEq3"> <mml:math display="inline"> <mml:msubsup> <mml:mi>p</mml:mi> <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">T</mml:mi> <mml:mrow> <mml:mi>ch</mml:mi> <mml:mspace width="0.25em"></mml:mspace> <mml:mi>jet</mml:mi> </mml:mrow> </mml:msubsup> </mml:math> <tex-math id="IEq3_TeX">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$$ {p}_{\textrm{T}}^{\textrm{ch}\ \textrm{jet}} $$\end{document}</tex-math> </inline-formula> < 100 GeV/ c, and compared to predictions from the PYTHIA 8 and Herwig 7 event generators. The distributions can also be calculated analytically with a leading hadronization correction related to the non-perturbative component of the Collins-Soper-Sterman (CSS) evolution kernel. Comparisons to analytical predictions at next-to-leading-logarithmic accuracy with leading hadronization correction implemented from experimental extractions of the CSS kernel in Drell-Yan measurements are presented. The analytical predictions describe the measured data within 20% in the perturbative regime, with surprising agreement in the non-perturbative regime as well. These results are compatible with the universality of the CSS kernel in the context of jet substructure.
